column168: OUR DRIVER ROLLED THIS TRUCK BECAUSE HE ATTEMPTED A LEFT TURN AT AN INTERSECTION TOO FAST AFTER EXITING A STRAIGHT OFF-RAMP FROM THE FREEWAY.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED, VIA TRUCK RADIO, HIS DISPATCH CENTER IN PHOENIX.  THEY IN TURN CALLED THE YUMA FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS.  BOTH RESPONDED AND TOOK CONTROL UNTIL OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED.  OUR TRAILER HELD TIGHT (NO SPILL) THE FIRE DEPT. PLACED A SMALL BLANKET OF FOAM AROUND THE TRUCK IN CASE IT MIGHT LEAK.  OUR ERT DRILLED ALL COMPARTMENTS OF THE TANK AND PRODUCT WAS MOVED TO ANOTHER TRUCK.  ALL COMPARTMENTS ARE DOUBLE BULKHEADED; THE ROLL-OVER CAUSED A CRACK IN ONE OF THE BULKHEADS AND APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS LEAKED INTO THE ANNULAR SPACE BETWEEN THE BULKHEADS.  WHEN THE TRUCK WAS UP-RIGHTED THE 15 GALS. SPILLED THRU A DETECTION BUNG IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK ONTO THE ASPHALT ROADWAY.  THE ARIZONA ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY DEPARTMENT TOOK CONTROL OF THE SPILL AND DECLARED THE CLEAN UP TO BE COMPLETE.
column169: A DRIVERS SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD AT OUR PHOENIX TERMINAL TWO WEEKS PRIOR TO THIS ACCIDENT, COVERED WAS THE FACT THAT SPEED IS THE BIGGEST SINGLE CAUSE OF ROLLOVERS AROUND CURVES.  SINCE THE ACCIDENT A SAFETY POSTER HAD BEEN DISTRIBUTED TO ALL OUR TERMINALS THAT ADDRESSES THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS ACCIDNET (WITH PHOTO'S).  IN ADDITION, A DETAILED ANALYSIS OF THIS ROLLOVER WILL BE SHARED WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS DURING THE NEXT ROUND OF SAFETY MEETINGS BEGINNING FEBRUARY 8TH.

The shipper’s agent contacted the carrier to report that one drum in a shipment may be leaking.  Shortly after the shipment left its shipping location, the shipper reported to their agent that there was a spot of material on their dock where one of the drums had been.  The carrier’ Hazardous Materials Specialist contacted the driver, who checked the load and verified that one drum appeared to be leaking.  The shipment is in the trailer that it was picked up on. The material in the drum is very thick.  Only about a pint has leaked so far.  It is not in any danger of escaping from the trailer.  The HazMat specialist gave the driver instructions on containing the spill so that ther would be no further leakage and allowed hime to continue on toward the carrier’s nearest facility.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at the customer facility in Riverside, California, the hose came loose due to pressure caused by an open valve during transfer, which resulted in the release of approximately 1 quart of free product.  The pressure caused the free product to spray into the eyes and face of two employees, one Slay Transportation Co., Inc. employee, and one customer employee.  Apparently, the product left a burning sensation.  Both employees sought medical attention at JFK Memorial Hospital and were admitted for observation.  The consignee performed the cleanup using an absorbent rag and neutralized the free product.  Spent material was placed along with like waste at the facility, to be held for proper disposal.  No further action is required at this time.  Both employees were released following observation with no additional symptoms.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to an open valve during transfer, which results in an over-pressurized hose, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines to all employees.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading at the consignee, PrintPak, facility, one, fifty-five gallon steel drum was discovered damaged inside the trailer by the Dawes Transport Inc., driver.  Apparently the release was the result of a puncture to the bottom of the drum.  Approximately 30 gallons of free product were released and affected the surrounding pallets and cargo.  The PrintPak facility contacted Envirosolve of Phoenix, Arizona to perform the cleanup.  Envirosolve placed cardboard and absorbent material to contain the free product.  The affected cargo and pallets were cleaned and repackaged.  Envirosolve placed contaminated pads and absorbents into one, fifty-five gallon drum.  Envirosolve will coordinate disposal. The one damaged fifty-five gallon drum was left at the terminal pending PrintPak instructions.  The remainder of the shipment was accepted by the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.

column168: SEE ATTACHED SHEET FOR SUMMARY AND PICTURES (typed summary, but picture may not be included in this text)    On February 1, 2005 while unloading containers at the final destination, the Gold Coast Freightways driver noticed a small leak from one of the drums.  A response crew was dispatched to the scene within minutes of notification.  Once the spill response crew arrived on-site, a small puncture was found in one poly 55-gallon drum of Fluorosilicic Acid.  The drum was overpacked into a poly 85-gallon salvage drum.  The spill in the trailer, on the asphalt surface of the parking lot, and the floor in the receiving facility was cleaned utilizing speedy dry and lime for neutralization.  The lime was applied multiple times until a neutral pH was obtained in the rinse water.  Seven drums of waste were generated from the cleanup.  The entire cleanup took approximately 6 hours for completion.    See below for picture of punctured drum.
column169: To prevent recurrance of this incident again, we suggest working with our shippers on inspection of pallets prior to loading of drums on them.  This may prevent protruding nails or other objects from impacting the drums and causing spills.    In addition, we will review with our drivers the importance of inspecting a load prior to leaving the shippers location(s).

column168: Terminal was sending the trailer out for delivery and needed a new placard bracket applied to the trailer. The terminal directed the driver to take the trailer by the vendor (on site) to apply a new placard bracket. The vendor was drilling holes into the trailer without checking the load position of the drums and drilled 2 holes into 1 drum. The terminal removed the drum from the trailer but did not remove the pallet the drum was on. The customer contacted a clean up team to come to their facility and handle the contaminated pallet and wipe off some drums. The same team came to our terminal, overpacked the damaged drum, wiped everything clean and disposed of the waste.
column169: Never perform work on a trailer without knowing the load position of the items inside of the trailer.

column168: The driver was in the process of unoloading sulfuric acid when the unloading hose ruptured. The unloading hose ruptured just behind the fitting that attaches to the discharge assembly on the rear of the trailer.The driver immedately shut down the unloading process by using the energency shut-off system on the trailer. The driver immediately called CTL Distribution to report the product release. CTL Distribution notified SATCO of the release and SATCO immediately responded. SATCO personnal contained the spill and put down soda ash to neutralize the sulfuric acid. SATCO contacted Southeast Industrial to manage the clean up. The required clean up was completed in the same day. SATCO took full responsibility for the unloading hose malfuction and the product release and perform the required clean up at SATCO's expense.

column168: UPON OPENING UP THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD PRODUCTS COMING UP ON THE DALLAS SHUTTLE, THE WAREHOUSE PERSONEL NOTICED THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS APPROXIMATELY 2/3 COVERED BY LIQUID.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, HE FOUND IT TO BE LEAKING A 55 GAL. STEEL DRUM OF STEPOSOL CA-207.  THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED, AND A SMALL HOLE WAS FOUND IN THE BOTTOM OF THE RUPTURED DRUM, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ONTO THE FLOOR.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED, BOTTOM SIDE UP, AND SEALANT PUTTY WAS APPLIED TO COVER THE HOLE AND PREVENT FURTHER LEAKING.  THE DRUM WAS THEN PLACED IN AN METAL OVERPACK.  FLOOR DRY/ABSORBENT WAS APPLIED TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER TO SOAK UP AS MUCH OF THE SPILL ON THE TRAILER AS POSSIBLE.  THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT AND THE ABSORBENT USED TO SOAK UP THE SPILL WAS, PLACED IN METAL OVERPACKS AND MARKED AS POTENTIAL WASTE.  THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO ENVIRO SOLVE TO HAVE THE CLEANING SAFELY AND LEGALLY COMPLETED.
column169: WE ARE WORKING WITH THE DALLAS OFFICE TO DETERMINE THE BEST METHOD OF PREVENTION OF THIS OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.  THE PALLETS ON WHICH THIS REPORT IS SHIPPED MUST BE IN GOOD REPAIR AND LOAD SECUREMENT IS BEING ADDRESSED.  THIS WAS A SMALL INCIDENT, BUT COULD HAVE BEEN WORSE, HAD IT NOT BEEN CAUGHT, OR HAD THIS HAPPEN ON  A WEEKEND, ALLOWING FURTHER UNDETECTED LEAKAGE, CAUSING A BIGGER SPILL OR WORSE.  ATTENTION TO LOAD SECUREMENT AND STORAGE/SHIPPING PROCEDURES MUST BE ADHERED TO AND CONSTANTLY MONITORED TO HELP PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: Prior to making the shipment, the shipper had the contents of two drums of spent solvent tested to determine their haz mat status.  One of the two containers passed screening tests.  Upon making the pick up, no differentiation was made, and both containers were accepted as non regulated material.  Upon screening at the receiving facility, it was discovered that one of the two drums was a flammable liquid.  In consultation with the shipper, the transporter assigned a proper hazardous material description, applied the appripriate markings and label, and generated a properly prepared shipping paper for return shipment.  The drum was determined to be of an appropriate specification, and was closed according to the original manufacturer's requirements.  The reclassified shipment was delivered to the original shipper without incident.

column168: THe driver was in route to a Service Station in Arecibo. He used the road #165 instead of the highway, because he wanted to stop for something to eat. It was 4:20 a.m. when, acording to the driver, a car coming in the opposite direction invaded his lane. The driver had to manouver to the right to avoid crashing with the vehicle. In doing so the tires went of the shoulder but he was able to take the truck on the road again. Even when he was able to take the truck back on track, themovement and weight of the product in the tank took over the truck and cuased to fall down on its right side. In that moment the truck and tank sled over the raod for aprpximaetly 250 feet and then stopped.     The driver called the Operations Coordinator inmediately, who then contacted the Safety Manager. The emergency response unit from Camioneros was inmediately activated and sent to the accident scene. In the meanwhile the driver and the Operations coordinator began the spill control measures. THe Safety Manager contacted Indutech, a contractor clean up comany, at 4:35 a.m. The Camioneros brugade got to the scene at 5:15 a.m. and began the spill control and the clean-up procedure. The road was closed by teh Police Department at approximately 4:40 a.m. The Fire Department and the Emergency Management Agency where at the site to help mitigate the possibility of a fire or explosion.     The spill source was found to be the air inward vent that when the tank hit the raod broke and let the product out. The source was cloged and the transfer procedure was started inmediately. A 6,000 gallon tank truck and another tractor with a 10,000 gallon tank were brought to make the transfer. The transfer took approximately 5 hours to complete. Once the transfer was done the truck was lifted using two cranes and hauled away to the Camioneros' premises.     Once the tank and truck were taken away the claun up work continued until 3:15 p.m. when the EQB declared the site safe and awarded permission to re-open the road. All the waste generated was punt on a 20 Yard container and tested for disposal al the site, then it was taken to Camioneros to store it until the lab results and the waste manifest are approved for disposal.
column169: Since it was determined that the driver did not follow procedures by not taking the designated route for that trip, a meeting with all drivers was held two days following the accident. During that meeting the drivers were reminded of the approved routes for each trip and were advised that failure to follow these routes would  result in severe sanctions. On the other hand a couple of weeks prior the accident an Accident Policy for Camioneros Cooperativa was developed and published and it will be effective on the 15th of March 2005.

column25: Mahogany Co. of Mays Landing, Inc.
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While travelling in Alberta, Virginia, the Mahogany Company driver lost control of the vehicle, which resulted in a vehicle overturn at 25888 Christanna Highway.  The driver was fatally injured as a result of the accident.  The Alberta Volunteer Fire Department, Virginia State Police, and Virginia Department of Environmental Quality responded to assess the site.  Apparently, the top of the trailer had been breached, which caused the freight to fall from the trailer, and into the yard at the incident location.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services of Prince George, Virginia was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection, it was determined that one (1) 2,500 pound tote of resin solution, had released approximately 20 gallons of free liquid.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of acetone had also been damaged, which resulted in the release of approximately 1 gallon of free product.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services excavated the affected soil and offloaded the remaining freight.  The leaking tote, and drum, were overpacked and held for disposition.  Seven (7) 55-gallon drums of contaminated soil were recovered during the cleanup.  Disposal will be coordinated per local, state and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported as a result of the hazardous materials.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and occurred as a result of a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Mahogany Company will continue to reinforce proper handling and driver safety guidelines to all employees.

column168: While in transit a process relief valve failed on the off-loading line. This valve is used in the off-loading process to monitor line pressure while off-loading. The driver isolated the process relief valve mechanically to stop the leak. The driver was notifed by a passenger vehicle following behind the trailer. The driver pulled to into a turn lane and assess the situation and notified CTL Distribution. CTL Distribution contacted Cura Emergency Service to manage the clean up. JBR Environmental was contacted by Cura Emergency Service and JBR sent out a two man crew to clean up the 20 gallon resin spill that had been contained on an asphalt surface. JBR put down oil dry on the spilled product and the spilled product and oil dry was place in 2-55 gallon drum and removed by JBR for disposal.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TO LOAD-OUT USING A REMOTE LOAD-OUT LINE AT THIS TANK BATTERY SITE.  THIS WAS THE FIRST TIME THE DRIVER HAD BEEN TO THIS LOCATION.  TIME OF DAY WAS APPROXIMATELY 1:00 A.M. MST.  THE DRIVER HAD HOOKED UP HOSES FROM THE TRUCK TO THE REMOTE LOAD LIVE.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED INTO THE TANK BETTERY AREA TO OPEN THE VALVE ON THE TANK.  TO THE SOUTH OF THIS VALVE WAS ANOTHER VALVE.  DRIVER STATES HE THOUGHT BOTH VALVES NEEDED TO BE OPENED IN ORDER TO LOAD THE TRUCK.  DRIVER BEGAN LOADING PROCESS.  DRIVER NOTED LOAD OUT PROCESS WAS A SLOW OPERATION.  HE PROCEEDED TO WALK BACK INTO THE TANK BATTERY AREA AND NOTED OIL IN THE CONTAINMENT DIKE SURROUNDING THE TANK BATTERY.  THE DRIVER THEN CEASSED OPEATIONS, CLOSED VALVES, AND LEFT LOAD OUT SITE.  OIL FROM TANK BACK FLOWED INTO LOAD LINE FOR WATER PIT.  WATER PITFILLED AND OVERFLOWED WITH CRUDE OIL.
column169: VALVES AT THE TANK BATTERIES TO BE CLEARLY MARKED AND DISTINGUISHED FROM ONE ANOTHER.  "FIRST RUNS" (FIRST VISIT TO A TANK BATTERY) WILL BE MADE DURING DAYLIGHT HOURS. column168: THIS DRUM WAS DROPPED AND LEAKED ABOUT 1 LITER.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED AND DID NOT GET INTO ANY DRAINS.

1.  FORT TRANSFER DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO PICK UP A LOAD FOR K.A. STEEL AT THEIR ST. LOUIS AREA LOCATION ON FRIDAY JANUARY, 28, 2005 FOR A DELIVERY ON SATURDAY, JANUARY 29, 2005 IN LOUISVILLE, KY.  THE PRODUCT HAD NOT BEEN LOADED ONTO OUR TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT AND WAS NOT READY FOR TRANSPORT AT THAT TIME.  2.  AN OUTSIDE SERVICE WAS BEING USED BY K.A. STEEL TO EMPTY A TANK OF PRODUCT.  THIS WAS THE FINAL LOAD OF A DILUTED SOLUTION OF PRODUCT.  IT WAS REMOVED FROM THE STORAGE TANK, AND LOADED INTO THEIR UNIT.  FROM THERE IT WAS THEN LOADED INTO THE FORT TRANSFER TRAILER FOR MOVEMENT TO THEIR CUSTOMER.  WHEN THE PRODUCT WAS LOADED INTO THE FORT TRANSFER TRAILER IT WAS PUMPED FROM THEIR UNIT INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE FORT UNIT.  THIS WAS COMPLETE AND THE FORT TRAILER SAT OVER THE WEEKEND.  3.  THE FORT TRANSFER DRIVER RETURNED TO PICK THE LOAD ON MONDAY, JANUARY 31, 2005, AND COMPLETE THE DELIVERY TO ALLIED DRUM IN LOUISVILLE, KY ON TUESDAY FEBRUARY 1, 2005  4.  THE FORT TRANSFER DRIVER ARRIVED AT ALLIED DRUM AROUND NOON ON FEBRUARY, 1, 2005.  HE WAS TOLD THAT THEY DID HAVE ROOM FOR THE PRODUCT AT THAT TIME AND TO DELIVER IT TO A "SLOP TANK" ON THE SIDE OF THE FACILITY.  5.  THE FORT DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY POINT AND SET THE TRAILER FOR THE DELIVERY.  THIS INCLUDED ATTACHING THE HOSE CONNECTIONS, SETTING UP PRESSURE IN THE TANK, AND OPENING THE VALVES.  6.  NO PRODUCT CAME OUT.  THE DRIVER RECHECKED ALL OF THE EQUIPMENT ANOTHER TIME TO SEE THAT THE VALVES WERE OPEN, THE HOSES WERE CONNECTED CORRECTLY, AND THAT THERE WAS PRESSURE IN THE TANK, AND OPENING THE VALVES.  6.  NO PRODUCT CAME OUT.  THE DRIVER RECHECKED ALL OF THE EQUIPMENT ANOTHER TIME TO SEE THAT THE VALVES WERE OPEN, THE HOSES WERE CONNECTED CORRECTLY, AND THAT THERE WAS PRESSURE IN THE TANK.  STILL NO PRODUCT CAME OUT.  7.  THE DRIVER RELEASED THE PRESSURE FROM THE TANK, CLOSED THE VALVES, AND REMOVED THE HOSE.  8.  AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER REMOVED THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS FROZEN IN THE 4 INCH DIAMETER LINE THAT RUNS ALONG THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER FROM THE EXTERNAL VALVE TO THE INTERNAL VALVE.  9.  THE DRIVER THEN TRIED TO CLEAR THE FROZEN LINE WITH WATER AND AN OLD BROOM HANDLE.  HE WAS UNSUCCESSFUL AT CLEARING THE PLUGGED LINE IN THIS MANNER.  HE ASKED THE PEOPLE ASSISTING HIM IF THEY HAD A STEAM LINE AVAILABLE.  THEY INDICATED THAT THEY DID, BUT THAT HE WOULD HAVE TO MOVE THE UNIT TO REACH IT.  HE THEN MOVED THE UNIT 300 FEET FORWARD TO THE REACH THE STEAM LINE.  HE USED THE STEAM LINE TO MELT THE ICE AND CLEAR THE LINE.  HE SAID THAT IT WORKED WELL, AND THAT HE WAS STARTING TO REPLACE THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND CLAMP WHEN PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW OUT.  12.  THE DRIVER AGAIN CHECKED THE HYDRAULIC KNOB, TURNING IT BACK AND FORTH.  HE RAN TO THE FRONT OF THE UNIT AND HIT THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF.  PRODUCT STILL WAS COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT AND HEAVY FLOW, IT WAS NOT ADVISABLE TO ATTEMPT TO REPLACE THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  PERSON
column169: 1.  WHEN THE TRAILER WAS RETURNED THE VALVE SYSTEM WAS CHECKED.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE HAD FOREIGN MATERIAL LODGED IN IT.  IT IS ASSUMED THAT THE MATERIAL CAME FROM INSIDE OF THE BULK STORAGE TANK THAT WAS BEING EMPTIED.  THUS THE VALVE WAS KEPT IN THE OPEN POSITION AND UNABLE TO BE CLOSED.  I AM TOLD THAT THE PRODUCT HAS A FREEZING POINT OF AROUND 50 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT.  SINCE THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN FORCED INTO THE TRAILER FROM THE BOTTOM RATHER THAN LOADING FROM THE DOME LID IT MAKES SENSE THAT ANY PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE BOTTOM LINE WOULD HAVE FROZEN.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD WOULD THEN HAVE HAD TO DO SOMETHING WITH THE LINE IN ORDER TO OPEN IT SO THE DELIVERY COULD BE COMPLETED.  2.  THE DRIVER MADE AN ASSUMPTION, BASED ON WHAT HE FELT HAD OCCURRED WHEN HE USED THE ALL OF THE CORRECT CONTROLS, THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE IN THE TRAILER WAS CLOSED.  WITH THIS ASSUMPTION HE THEN REMOVED THE EXTERNAL VALVE IN AN ATTEMPT TO SEE WHAT WAS CAUSING THE BLOCKAGE IN THE LINE.  THAT IS WHERE THE DRIVER MADE HIS MISTAKE.  AFTER HAVING REMOVED THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND DISCOVERING THE LINE TO BE FROZEN, IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN REPLACED AGAIN BEFORE ATTEMPTING TO CLEAR THE LINE.  BOTH THE DRIVER AND THE PEOPLE ASSISTING HIM WHEN HE ASKED ABOUT A STEAM LINE MISSED THIS STEP.  AGAIN, THROUGH BOTH ASSUMED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS CLOSED AS IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN.  3.  IN A SITUATION LIKE THIS IF A LINE IS DISCOVERED TO BE BLOCKED BY FROZEN PRODUCT, THE VALVES SHOULD BE LEFT IN PLACE, AND HEAT APPLIED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE LINE IN ORDER TO MELT THE FROZEN PRODUCT.  BUT, PRIOR TO APPLYING THE HEAT, THE DRIVER NEEDS TO BE AWARE OF THE NATURE OF THE PRODUCT IN THE LINE, TO BE SURE IT WILL NOT HAVE AN ADVERSE REACTION TO THE APPLICAITON OF HEAT!  A BUCKET OR RECEPTACLE CAN BE PLACED AT THE END OF THE LINE AND THE EXTERNAL VALVE CRACKED OPEN TO ALLOW THE PRODUCT TO COME OUT AND NOT BUILD UP PRESSURE AS MELTING OCCURS.  THE PRODUCT CAUGHT IN THE BUCKET CAN THEN BE GIVEN TO THE CUSTOMER FOR THEIR DISPOSAL OR PROCESSING THE SAME AS FOR NORMAL PRODUCT LEFT IN THE LINE OR HOSES THAT ARE EMPTIED AT THE END OF A DELIVERY.  4.  A REVIEW OF THIS PROCESS WILL BE PASSED ON TO ALL OUR DRIVERS SO THEY WILL BE KNOWLEDGEABLE OF "WHAT TO DO" IN ANY SIMILAR BLOCKED LINE SITUATIONS.

THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TURNED THE PUMP OFF.  DRIVER ESTIMATES THAT BETWEEN 10 AND 15 GALLONS SPILLED OVER THE TOP.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE CUSTOMER'S RETENTION WALL.

OUR DRIVER WAS TRANSFERING PRODUCT FROM OUR TANK TRUCK TO THE CUSTOMER'S TOTES.  HE WAS DIRECTED TO ANOTHER LOCATION TO FILL A TOTE (WHERE IT IS USED ONSITE) NEXT TO A ROAD.  THE PRODUCT HOSE IS NOT SECURED IN ANY FASHION.  IT IS SIMPLY INSERTED INTO AN OPENING IN THE TOP OF THE TOTE.  THE DRIVER WAS POSITIONED AT THE REAR OF THE TRUCK ON THE PASSENGER SIDE (BECAUSE OF THE PORTION OF THE TRUCK IN RELATIONSHIP WITH THE ROAD).  DURING THE UNLOAIDNG/TRANSFER PROCESS THE PRODUCT HOUSE CAME OUT OF THE TOTE AND PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND AND ENTERED THE WATER.  WAY NEXT TO THE TOTE.  THE DRIVER HAD TO TRAVEL AROUND THE FRONT OF THE VEHICLE TO STOP THE FLOW WITH THE EMERGENCY CUT OFF.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 8, 2005, THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN ON A TRUCK OPERATING UNDER THE AUTHORITY OF MEDICAL DELIVERY SERVICES, INC (MDS) AN AUTHORIZED CARRIER OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER, MR. GHAZARYAN, SAW THE PACKAGE WAS PRESENT AT CARDINAL PHARMACY, 640 SOUTH JEFFERSON STREET, PLACENTIA.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 PM, UPON ARRIVAL AT MALLINCKRODT, INC, 11368 MOUNTAIN VIEW AVE, LOMA LINDA, THE TRUCK'S TAILGATE WAS DOWN AND THE PACKAGE WAS MISSING.  NO STOPS WERE MADE BETWEEN THE TWO LOCATIONS AND THE MAJORITY OF THE ROUTE INVOLVED HIGHWAY 91.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED MDS MANAGEMENT.  CARDINAL PHARMACY WAS CONTACTED TO SEARCH THEIR INVENTORY AND IMMEDIATE AREA.  THE DRIVER BACK TRACKED HIS ROUTE TWICE, BUT COULD NOT FIND THE PACKAGE.  WITHIN TWO HOURS OF NOTICING THE PACKAGE WAS MISSING, THE CALIFORNIA EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR WAS CONTACTED.  CONTROL NUMBER 05-0874 WAS ASSIGNED AND THE INFORMATION WAS FORWARDED TO JOHN HARRIS OF THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH SERVICES.  UPON ADVICE FROM THE LOCAL DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH SERVICES REPRESENTATIVE, MR. ROBERT GREGOR, THE ORANGE COUNTY CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL WAS CONTACTED.  THE SIZE, MARKING, AND NATURE OF THE PACKAGE WAS EXPLAINED BY THE MDS CONSULTANT, DR. GEORGE HARDER TO SGT. PORTIO.  THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION WAS CONVEYED.  THE PACKAGE CONTAINS RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL USED IN A MEDICAL PROCEDURE.  THE VIAL IS LOCATED IN A LEAD SHIELDED CONTAINER AND SHOULD SUSTAIN SOME IMPACTS.  THIS IS A VERY SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL THAT IS NOT DANGEROUS.  IF FOUND, THE PACKAGE SHOULD BE PUT IN A PLASTIC BAG AND MDS WILL SEND A DRIVER FOR PICK UP.  THE AREA WHERE THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND WILL BE SURVEYED TO IDENTIFY ANY SPILLAGE.  IF THE FINDING OFFICER DOES NOT DESIRE TO TOUCH THE PACKAGE, NO MORE THAN SIX FEET OF SPACE NEED BE CORDONED OFF.
column169: PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATIONS CONCLUDED THAT THE PACKAGE POSSIBLY FELL OUT OF THE DRIVER'S VEHICLE WHILE IN TRANSIT FROM CARDINAL HEALTHCARE IN PLACENTIA, CA TO MALLINCKRODT IN LOMA LINDA, CA.  UPON THIS DETERMINATION, THE MANUFACTURER WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  AFTER NUMEROUS ATTEMPTS TO RECOVER THE MISSING PACKAGE BY RETRACING THE DRIVER'S ROUTE, AND WITH NO SUCCESS, IT WAS DETERMINED THE PACKAGE HAD INDEED BEEN LOST.  HAVING KNOWLEDGE OF THIS, GEORGE HARDER (MDS RSO/HEALTH PHYSICIST) AND I BEGAN NOTIFYING THE APPROPRIATE LOCAL AND STATE AGENCIES.  MEDICAL DELIVERY SERVICES IS EXTREMELY CONSCIENTIOUS OF THE REGULATORY PROCEDURES AND MAKES EVERY EFFORT TO CONVEY THE SAME IMPORTANCE TO OUR DRIVERS.  MR. GHAZARYAN RECEIVED MDS'S ANNUAL RECURRENT HAZMAT AND SECURITY TRAINING AS RECENT AS JANUARY 18TH 2005.  THERE IS NO EXCUSE FOR THIS INCIDENT.  MDS'S CORRECTIVE ACTION WILL BE EFFECTIVE IMMEDIATELY AND ENSURES THAT MR. GHAZARYAN WILL NOT HANDLE ANY MALLINCKRODT MATERIAL.  ALSO, MDS WILL READDRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF BLOCKING AND BRACING AS DESCRIBED IN CFR 49 393.104 WITH EACH DRIVER THAT HANDLES OR HAS THE POTENTIAL TO HANDLE ANY MALLINCKRODT FREIGHT.

column168: ON 2/03/05, A FRA INSPECTOR NOTICED TRAILER REAZ 215567 IN BNSF'S SEATTLE INTERMODAL HUB PARKING AREA WITH INCOMPLETE PLACARDING ON TRAILER.  THIS TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO CONTAINMENT AREA FOR INSPECTION, AS CURRENT BILLING INDICATED NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTENTS.  THE INSPECTION REVEALED VARIOUS SMALL PACKAGES OF LABELED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WHICH INCLUDED THREE FIVE GALLON POLY JERRICANS OF CLASS 8 CORROSIVES, THREE FIVE GALLON METAL PAILS OF CLASS 3, UN1133, PG II ADHESIVES, AND NUMEROUS CONSUMER SIZED SPRAY CANS OF PAINT RELATED MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS PRODUCT RELEASES ASSOCIATED WITH THIS EVENT.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION INDICATED THAT REAZ 215567 ORIGINATED FROM WHITE EARTH, ND FROM BNSF SALVAGE OPERATIONS FOR A PREVIOUS INTERMODAL TRAIN DERAILMENT THAT OCCURRED ON 1/16/05.  APPARENTLY, BNSF SALVAGE AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS INADVERTENTLY PLACED THIS HAZARODUS MATERIAL INTO SALVAGE TRAILER REAZ 215567 ALONG WITH OTHER RECOVERED LADING THAT WAS ORIGINALLY SHIPPED IN TRAILER SFTZ 222241 WHICH WAS INVOLVED IN THE AFOREMENTIONED DERAILMENT.  SFTZ 222241 WAS ORIGINALLY BILLED AS NON-HAZARDOUS FAK.  REAZ 215567'S BILLING WAS GENERATED INCORRECTLY USING THE BILLING INFORMATION BASED ON SFTZ 222241'S ORIGINAL EDI BILLING, RATHER THAN USING BILLING REPRESENTING THE ACTUAL CONTENTS WITHIN THIS SALVAGE TRAILER.  * THE ADHESIVES WERE ORIGINALLY SHIPPED AND BILLED PROPERLY IN TRAILER USAZ 234537 WHICH WAS DAMAGED IN THE AFOREMENTIONED DERAILMENT AT WHITE EARTH ON 1/16/05.
column169: IN ORDER TO AVOID FUTURE ERRANT BILLINGS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS FROM BNSF DERAILMENT SALVAGE OPERATIONS, PROPER SHIPMENT DESCRIPTIONS AND BILLING PROCEDURES WILL BE REITERATED TO THE BNSF CONTRACTORS INVOLVED IN SALVAGE OPERATIONS AND PROCESSES.

column168: I RESPONDED TO A STAINED PACKAGE AT THE RED SECONDARY.  WEARING PROPER PPE AND FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE, I TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE TO THE PSC AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGING MATERIALS.  INSPECTION OF CONTENTS REVEALED 13 AEROSOL CANS AND OTHER HAIR CARE PRODUCTS.  THE CANS WERE ALL INSIDE THE BOX WITH NO CUSHIONING NOR WERE THERE ANY ORM-D LABELS OR OTHER WARNIGN ALBELS ON OUTER CARTON.  THE AEROSOL CANS THAT WERE LEAKING WAS CAUSED BY NO CAPS ON THE AEROSOL CANS CAUSING THEM TO DISCHARGE.

column168: Driver Danny Lanford was driving a bulk truck on Maysville Road during heavy rains. The front passenger side tire got off the edge of the road, then the rear tire went off the road. The embankment pulled the wheels down to the right, causing the vehicle to rollover. The truck overturned in the roadway. The release of propane came from a 3' pipe that connects to the delivery hose. The piping broke when the truck overturned. The propane disippated.
column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: Driver was on private property making a propane delivery to a 57 gallon cylinder installed onto a mobile cooking trailer. Twelve gallons had been pumped into the cylinder to perform tests, when the driver noticed the bottom of the cylinder began to leak. The driver removed the fill hose and instructed a few people in the area to stay away from the cylinder. The release lasted 5 to 10 minutes. As the driver was figuring out how to remove the cylinder, the escaping gas ignited. The Venice Fire Departmen extinguished the fire. The front of the mobile unit and two tents were damaged. Inspection showed a pinhole located on the bottom of the cylinder. There were no injuries.
column169: Reinforcement to employees on company policies for pre-fill inspections and DOT requirements.

BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND DRIPPING HYDROCHLORIC ACID (HCL) FROM A HOLE IN THE SUMP AREA.  RESPONDERS PLACED A RECEPTACLE WITH SODA ASH INSIDE UNDER THE SUMP TO CATCH DRIPS.  A WOODEN PLUG WAS INSERTED IN THE SMALL HOLE AND SODA ASH WAS POURED INTO THE TANK CAR TO NEUTRALIZE AND SOLIDIFY A SMALL AMOUNT OF HCL (ESTIMATED AT ONE GALLON) REMAINING INSIDE THE TANK CAR.  SODA ASH WAS ALSO DISTRIBUTED ONTO THE IMPACTED GROUND TO NEUTRALIZE HCL SPILLAGE.  THE PRODUCT DRIP WAS STOPPED AT APPROX. 2145 HRS. CST (2/15).  SUSPECT INTERIOR LINING WAS COMPROMISED IN THE SUMP AREA THAT RESULTED IN THE SMALL CORROSION HOLE OF THE TANK SHELL.  THE PREVIOUS UNLOADER OF THE HCL (BASIC CHEMICAL) REPORTED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS OFF COLOR WHEN UNLOADED.  NATX 210016 WAS BEING DIVERTED TO A RAIL CAR REPAIR FACILITY (H C CHANDLER) FOR LINING INSPECTION AND WARRANTED REPAIRS.  FRA-05020059 MOVEMENT APPROVAL GRANTED TO SEND NATX 210016 TO THE AFOREMENTIONED RAIL CAR REPAIR FACILITY FOR CLEANING, PURGING AND REPAIR.
column169: PENDING RESULTS OF NATX 210016'S INSPECTION AT REPAIR FACILITY.

column168: ON FEB 22, 2005 2:00 AM A COMPANY DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT A COMPANY STATION.  WHILE UNLOADING DRIVER DID NOT SECURELY LOCK DOWN THE FITTING AFTER MOVING THE DELIVERY HOSE FROM ONE TANK TO ANOTHER.  HE OPENED TRAILER VALVE AND GASOLINE SPILLED FROM HOUSE, THROUGH THE FITTING AND ONTO THE PAVEMENT IN THE STATION.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE VALVE.  AN ESTIMATED 25 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS SPILLED.  THE STATION ATTENDANT WAS NOTIFIED, THE STATION WAS SHOT DOWN, AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED.  THE DRIVER PUT DOWN SPILL PADS TO STOP THE FLOW AND ABSORB THE GAS.  OIL DRY WAS ALSO PUT DOWN TO ABSORB PRODUCT.  FIRE FIGHTERS AND DRIVER PUT DOWN ADDITIONAL SPILL PADS TO PREVENT RAN OFF TO STORM SEWER.  TERMINAL TECHNICIAN WENT OUT TO SITE TO CLEAN UP SPILL.
column169: INVESTIGATION TEAM CONSISTING OF TWO FLEET MANAGERS AND A DRIVER TRAINER MET TO REVIEW INCIDENT AND INTERVIEW DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE SPILL.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED CAUSING HIM TO FORGET TO LOCK DOWN FITTING.  RECOMMEND SHARING INCIDENT WITH OTHER DRIVERS TO EMPASISE IMPORTANCE OF CHECKING AND RECHECKING ALL CONNECTIONS.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT 1ST AND SOUTH MAIN IN COUPEVILLE WAS, 98239, DRIVER PROCEEDED TO CHECK TANK MONITOR SYSTEM AND MAKE SURE PRODUCT WOULD FIT WITHIN 90% ULLAGE OF TANK.  DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT WOULD FIT WITHIN 90% ULLAGE, SO HE DROPPED PRODUCT INTO REGULAR TANK.  AT THE VERY END OF DROP TRUBE THEN THE PRODUCT STARTED TO RISE IN SPILL BUCKET.  DRIVER TURNED OFF FLOW TO UNDERGROUND TANK, AND THEN REMOVED PRODUCT HOUSE FROM DROP TRUBE.  AFTER DRIVER REMOVED HOSE FROM DROP TUBE, PRODUCT FLOWED OUT OF DROP TUBE AND ONTO TANK PAD (CEMENT).  DRIVER VERY QUICKLY PLACED DROP TUBE LID ON THE DROP TUBE AND STOPPED THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT OUT OF TANK.  THEN HE USED ABSORBENT PADS TO STOP FLOW OF PRODUCT, ALONG WITH WIPING UP AND CONTAINING THE ENTIRE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT HAD EXITED TANK.  THE ESTIMATED TIME OF RELEASE WAS ABOUT SIX TO SEVEN SECONDS.  AFTER PRODUCT WAS WIPED UP HE USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP REMAINING PRODUCT LEFT ON CEMENT AND ASPHALT.  PRODUCT NEVER CAME IN CONTACT WITH DIRT OR WATER AND WAS CONTAINED ON CEMENT AND ASPHALT AT ALL TIMES.
column169: AFTER THIS OCCURRENCE WE HAD OUR REPAIR AND MAINTENANCE COMPANY (NORTHWEST PUMP & EQUIPMENT) OUT TO SITE TO REPROGRAM TANK MONITORING SYSTEM AND TO CHECK THE STATUS OF UNDER GROUND TANK TO MAKE SURE IT WAS FUNCTIONING PROPERLY.  AFTER REPROGRAMMING THE TANK MONITOR TO THE EXACT VOLUME OF FUEL IN TANK THIS PROBLEM WILL BE AVOIDED IN THE FUTURE.  AFTER THIS OCCURRENCE WE WILL NO LONGER DISPATCH LOADS CLOSE TO 90% ULLAGE FROM NOW ON.  WE HAVE ALSO TRAINED ALL DRIVERS TO ALWAYS CHECK TANK MONITORS AND MAKE SURE PRODUCT WILL FIT WELL WITHIN 90% ULLAGE.  WE HAVE ALSO TRAINED ALL DRIVERS NOT TO PULL OFF DROP HOSES IF THEY SEE PRODUCT IN SPILL BUCKET UNTIL THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK HAS STABILIZED IN THE TANK.  WE HAVE NEVER HAD THIS HAPPEN BEFORE AND WE FELL THAT WE CAN ELIMINATE THIS FROM EVER HAPPENING AGAIN, AT THIS SITE OR ANY OTHER THAT WE DELIVER TO.

column168: WHILE LOADING A PALLET IN BEHIND SEVERAL DRUMS OF FLAM. LIQUID, THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR FAILED TO MAKE SURE THE BLADES WERE NOT EXTENDING BEYOND THE PALLET.  THE BLADE OF THE FORKLIFT SPEARED THE DRUM VERY CLOSE TO THE BOTTOM EDGE.  THE LEAK WAS NOT IMMEDIATELY DISCOVERED.  THE INCIDENT TOOK PLACE JUST BEFORE THE FACILITY CLOSED FOR THE DAY.  THE LEAK WAS FOUND BY THE FACILITY GUARD SERVICE DURING A ROUTINE PATROL.  THE LEAK WAS REPORTED TO THE OPERATORS MANAGER WHO RESPONDED FROM HOME & ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY WITHIN 30 MINUTES OF NOTIFICATION.  AFTER TAKING PROPER SAFETY PRECAUTION (SCBA/PROTECTIVE WEAR) THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED & CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL BEGAN.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS FOR DISPOSITION.
column169: A COMBINATION OF TRAINING/REINFORCING POLICIES ON PROPER DRUM HANDLING AND BETTER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUES.  ALSO EMPHASIZE SUPERVISOR ATTENTION TO DETAIL AND IMMEDIATE PREVENTION OF POSSIBLE PROBLEMS.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 9, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR BTAX 1017, LOADED WITH ARGO, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, UN1951, WAS REPORTED VENTING WHILE AT GENTRY, ARKANSAS KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE VAPORIZER INLET VALVE.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR A FIELD REPRESENTATIVE TO MEET THE CAR AT THE KCSR, NEOSHO, MO YARD.  THE FIELD REPRESENTATIVE CLOSED THE VALVE, THUS CORRECTING THE RELEASE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.  NOTE: PART IV, QUESTION 32: RESPONDER=$150 PER HOUR AT 5 HOURS ($750) AND $1.65 PER MILE AT 260 MILES ($429) TOTAL = ($1,179)  PART IV, QUESTION 28 (IF VALVE OR DEVICE FAILED): NO TYPE, MANUFACTURER, OR MODEL NUMBER IS MARKED, SINCE THERE WERE ONLY LOOSE CLOSURES.
column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS) WHERE POSSIBLE SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: EMPTY TANK # DCIU742027 WAS AT REST ON THE PORT FACILITY WHEN PORT PERSONNEL DISCOVERED A SPILL BELOW THE TANK.  AN INVESTIGATION REVEALED A CONSTANT DRIP FROM THE BARRELL OF THE EMPTY TANK.  THE SHIPPER AND OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE LEAK SEEMED TO BE FROM THE BARRELL OF THE TANK ITSELF.  THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR HANDLED THE SPILL, PUMPED OFF ANY ADDITIONAL RESIDUE FROM THE TANK AND CONFIRMED THE UNIT AS SAFE TO TRANSPORT.  THE SHIPPER REMOVED THE TANK FROM THE PORT.  FOLLOWING UP WITH THE SHIPPER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK BARREL WAS PITTED FROM THE INSIDE.

column168: TANK CAR, PPRX 55065, LOAD HEPTANES, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING CONTINUOUSLY FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GENTILLY YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA.  THE CAR WAS MOVED OVER THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL CONTAINMENT PANS TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT FLOWING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK.  THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE LA STATE PATROL WERE NOTIFIED OF THE PRODUCT RELEASE AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED ITS HAZMAT TEAM.  THE SHIPPER, CONOCOPHILLIPS CO., WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE WEEP HOLES ON THE SIDE OF THE 1 INCH THERMOMETER WELL TUBE ON TOP OF THE CAR.  THEY OPENED THE 1 INCH AIR LINE TO RELIEVE THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE THERMOMETER WILL ASSEMBLY WAS REMOVED AND THE TUBE WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN PREVIOUSLY PATCHED.  THE PATCHED AREA HAD A HOLE WORN THROUGH THE PATCH MATERIAL ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK INTO THE THERMOMETER WELL TUBE.  A 2 INCH THREADED PLUG WAS SCREWED INTO THE ORIFICE WHERE THE THERMOMETER WELL HAD BEEN REMOVED.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED AND THE MANWAY GASKET INSPECTED.  NO DEFECTS WERE FOUND WITH THE MANWAY GASKET.  THE CAR WAS NOTED TO HAVE ABOUT 7 INCHES OF OUTAGE IN THE TANK.  THE MANWAY WAS SECURED.  THE CAR IS BEING HELD PENDING THE SHIPPER'S APPLICATION FOR AN FRA APPROVAL TO COVER THE MOVE TO DESTINATION.  CONOCO PHILLIPS WAS ADVISED OF THE DEFECT FOUND ON THE CAR AND THE NEED FOR AN FRA APPROVAL TO MOVE THE CAR.

column168: FLIGHT 2355 THAT ORIGINATED IN CHICAGO (MDW) AND MAKES A SINGLE STOP IN ST. LOUIS (STL) ARRIVED AT HOUSTON HOBBY (HOU) AT APPROXIMATELY 1100 CENTRAL TIME.  RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED A CARGO SHIPMENT THAT HAD AN OILY RESIDUE LEAKING FROM THE PACKAGE ON ONE OF THE BOXES (3 BOXES WERE IN THE SHIPMENT.)  AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE WAS CONTACTED AND CLEANED UP THE RESIDUAL OIL THAT WAS DETERMINED TO BE HYDRAULIC OIL.  THE REPORT OF HYDRAULIC OIL DID NOT CAUSE CONCERN INITIALLY BECAUSE OF ITS NON-REGULATED NATURE AND ELEVATED FLASHPOINT.  UPON FURTHER REVIEW IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED INTERNAL COMBUSTION ENGINES THAT HAD SMALL AMOUNTS OF FUEL (GASOLINE) IN THE FUEL TANKS.  GAS ODOR WAS CONFIRMED BY THE AGENTS WORKING AT THE CARGO FACILITY AND ONE OF THE AGENTS NOTICED THAT GASOLINE WAS LEAKING AT THE GAS CAP OF THE ENGINE.  BASED ON THE FACT THAT THERE WAS RESIDUAL FUEL IN THE TANKS AND SINCE THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED AS CONTAINING NO DANGEROUS GOODS ON THE AIR WAYBILL, THE SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED AS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT VIA A DISCREPANCY REPORT TO THE FAA.

BNSF YARD SWITHC JOB PULLING A CUT OF RAILCARS IN RAILYARD, DERAILED FOUR RAILCARS AT A SWITCH THAT WAS OBSTRUCTED BY A LADING TIE-DOWN CHAIN CAUGHT IN THE SWITCH MECHANISM.  CELX 3272 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND PRODUCT LEAKED OUT FROM THE LQIUID AND VAPOR VALVES FLANGE AREAS.  SPILLAGE CONTAINED BY ABSORBENT PADS PLACED UNDER LEAK AREA.  BNSF RESPONDERS TIGHTENED ALL FLANGE NUTS ON EACH VALVES FLANGE MOUNTING STUDS, ENDING PRODUCT RELEASE BY 1900 HRS. PST, 2/24/05.  A BNSF CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM NEUTRALIZED AND REMEDIATED ALL GROUND IMPACT SPILLAGE.  DUE TO TANK CAR DAMAGE, CELX 3272 IS SCHEDULED TO HAVE ITS REMAINING PRODUCT TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR BY MONTH'S END.

ON ON MONDAY, FEBRUARY 28, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 7 AM, A MATERIALS HANDLING OPERATOR WAS CONNECTING A TUBE TRAILER TO LOAD ETHANE AT THE B-55 TRUCK TRACK.  WHEN A LEAK DEVELOPED ON THE LOAD LINE AFTER THE FIRST TUBE STARTED FILLING, THE OPERATOR ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE CONNECTION WITH A PIPE WRENCH.  THE OPERATOR INADVERTENTLY OPENED A BLEED VALVE WHEN HIS PIPE WRENCH SLIPPED, CONTACTING THE OVAL HANDLE OF THE BLEED VALVE.  THE BODY POSITION OF THE OPERATOR AND THE CONFIGURATION OF THE TRAILER LEFT THE OPERATOR IN THE DIRECT "LINE OF FIRE" TO BE THERMALLY BURNED FROM THE COLD LIQUID ETHANE THAT WAS RELEASED FROM THE LOAD LINE BLEED VALVE.  AFTER THE OPERATOR WAS KNOCKED BACK, HE WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND CLOSE THE BLEED VALVE BEFORE SEEKING MEDICAL ATTENTION.  A SECOND MATERIALS HANDLING OPERATOR FROM A NEARBY LOADING OPERATION TRANSPORTED THE INJURED OPERATOR TO EASTMAN MEDICAL WHERE HE WAS GIVEN FIRST AIDE AND LATER TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL.  THE OPERATOR WAS TREATED AS HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO PREVENT RECURRENCE INCLUDE: (1) REVISE PROCEDURES TO BLOCK IN PRESSURE SOURCE AND DEPRESSURE LINE BEFORE TIGHTENING LEAKS WHEN LOADING TRUCKS AND RAIL CARS.  (2) INVESTIGATE USING DIFFERENT CONNECTIONS THAT DO NOT REQUIRE A PIPE WRENCH OR OTHER WRENCH THAT CAN SLIP.  (3) REPLACE BALL VALVE WITH GATE VALVE TO PREVENT ACCIDENT OPENING.  (4) SCHEDULE PHA TO REVIEW CGA AND SPRINKLER COVERAGE AT LOADING RACK.

ON FEBRUARY 21, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 16:40 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR ACFX 78313, CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S., UN1993, PACKING GROUP II, WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE AT THE SHREVEPORT, LOUISIANA, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) RAILROAD YARD.  A KCSR REPRESENTATIVE INSPECTED THE TANK CAR DISCOVERING THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV) WAS DEFECTIVE.  KCSR CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WHO DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO REPLACE THE SRV.  A SECOND RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO REMOVE CORRODED BOLTS FROM THE SRV ASSEMBLY.  THE INITIAL RESPONSE TEAM REPLACED THE SRV ON FEBRUARY 23, 2005.  THE SHIPPER COULD NOT DO A LEAK PRESSURE TEST IN THE FIELD, SO THEY OBTAINED FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION (FRA) ARRPOVAL TO PROGRESS THE CAR TO ITS DESTINATION.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND NO INJURIES.  NOTE: SECTION III, QUESTION 32, RESPONSE COST: $ 3,478; $1612 - REMOVAL OF CORRODED NUTS AND BOLTS IN ORDER TO REPLACE THE SRV; $1,865 - REPLACEMENT FOR THE SRV.
column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR, AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: SKIDS CONTAINING THE 21 BAGS WERE UNLOADED ON DOCK, FREIGHT WAS DISCOVERED WITH RESIDUE LEAKING OUT.  EPS WAS CALLED IN TO REMOVE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THAT LEAKED OUT AND TO RECOUPE LEAKING BAGS.
column169: PROPERLY STAGE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AS NOT IN TRAFFIC AREA TO AVOID HITTING THEM.

column168: IT APPEARS THAT TRAILER 289434 FROM LEX HAD PRO 730 330 451 LEAKING WHILE IN TRANSIT FROM LEX TO SOH.  THERE WAS A HOLE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE DRUM.  IT LOOKS LIKE THE HOLE WAS CREATED BY THE DOOR WHEN IT WAS SHUT.  THE DRUM WAS TAKEN OFF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  OIL DRY WAS OPENED ON THE SPILLED INK TO DRY IT UP.
column169: FUTURE ACTIONS RECOMMENDED ARE USING SKIDS AS DUNNAGE ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.

column168: THE TRAILER WAS LOADED BY THE SHIPPER.  WHEN IT CAME TO THE DOCK TO BE UNLOADED WE OPENED THE DOOR AND THE SKID ON THE REAR WAS TIPPED OVER.  TWO BOTTLES HAD THE CAPS OFF AND 4 BOTTLES BROKE OPEN.  THE RELEASE MUST HAVE BEEN FOR A PERIOD OF SEVERAL HOURS.  THE LEAKING CONTENTS WERE ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND THE LEAKING BOTTLES WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER.
column169: THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO INSURE THAT THEY BLOCK IN AND BRACE THE FREIGHT ON THE REAR.

column168: THIS FREIGHT WAS LOADED WITH TOP FREIGHT ON TOP.  THE FREIGHT WASN'T LOADED WITH DUNNAGE TO PREVENT DAMAGES.  THE OTHER FREIGHTS WEIGHT BEND THE 1 METAL CAN IN 1 BOX.  THERE WERE A TOTAL OF 4 CANS IN THE BOX, BUT ONLY THE ONE CAN WAS DAMAGED AND SPILLING.  ABOUT 1 LITER SPILLED OUT.  REPORT #020405061
WHILE UNLOADING A SKID FROM THE TRAILER THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CARTON WAS ON TOP.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BOX FELL OFF OF THE SKID, CAUSING THE CARTON TO HIT THE FLOOR AND BURST OPEN.

column168: THE DOCKWORKER WAS GOING INTO THE TRAILER WITH THE DRUM ATTACHMENT.  WHILE TRYING TO GRAB THE DRUM, HE ENTERED AT A BAD ANGLE AND PUNCTURED A DRUM WITH THE ATTACHMENT.  HE MADE A HOLE 3 INCHES FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM ROUGHLY 2 IN LONG BY 3/4 INCHES WIDE.  HE NOTIFIED ME OF WHAT HAPPENED.  WE CALLED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOR CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING INBOUND TRAILER IN LEXINGTON, A SMALL QUANTITY OF LIQUID WAS NOTICED UNDER THE PALLET THAT SHIPMENT WAS ON.  ONE OF THE PALLET SLATS WAS ALSO WET. THIS CAUSED A VERY SMALL SPLIT IN BOTTOM OF DRUM.  APPROX. 1 PINT OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP.  REPAIR PUTTY WAS APPLIED TO DRUM TO STOP LEAK. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 AM THE DRIVER FOR HELENA CHEMICAL ENTERED INTO AN AREA OF SR 64 WITH DENSE FOG.  TO AVOID HITTING ANOTHER VEHICLE THE DRIVER HAD TO QUICKLY APPLY HIS BRAKES.  THE FORCEFUL STOP CAUSED THE TOTE TO SLIDE OUT FROM UNDER THE TIE DOWN STRAPS.  THE TOTE FELL OFF THE TRUCK AND ON TO THE SHOULDER OF SR 64, RUPTURING THE BODY AND LEAKING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS.  AT 9:07 AM A LOCAL SPILL CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED.  AT 10:30 AM THE SPILL CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SITE.  THE SITE HAS SINCE BEEN EXCAVATED AND BACKFILLED WITH CLEAN SOIL.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS DISPOSED OF AT A PERMITTED SUBTITLE D LANDFILL.

column168: A SWITCH CREW WORKING IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GOULDING YARD IN PENSACOLA, FL, REPORTED THEY INHALED SOME DUST WHICH GAVE THEM SCRATCHY THROATS AND A BAD TASTE IN THEIR MOUTHS.  THE CREW DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION AND CONTINUED TO WORK UNTIL THE END OF THEIR SHIFT.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT INVESTIGATED THIS REPORT TO DETERMINE IF A POSSIBLE CHEMICAL EXPOSURE HAD OCCURRED.  NO CHEMICAL CARS WERE FOUND IN THE YARD THAT COULD HAVE CAUSED THE SYMPTOMS THAT THE YARD CREW DESCRIBED.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SOLUTIA FACILITY IN GONZALEZ, FL, TO INSPECT THE CARS ON TRAIN, M73326, THAT HAD DEPARTED THE YARD ABOUT THE TIME THE CREW MEMBERS SAID THEY EXPERIENCED THEIR SYMPTOMS.  WHILE INSPECTING THE CAR IN THE TRAIN, THE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT TANK CAR, UTLX 48265, LOAD CYCLOHEXANONE, HAD A SLOW PRODUCT DRIP FROM THE PLUG ON THE BOTTOM OF THE 2 INCH AUXILLARY BALL VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED THE VALVE PLUG AND THE DRIP STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS THEN SWITCHED INTO SOLUTIA FOR UNLOADING.

Driver arrived at the consignee’s and advised them that he had Ferric Chloride to deliver. Consignee’s employee confirmed their tank had enough space to hold. product & touched the fill line that he wanted the driver to connect to. Driver connected to the line that he was shown and then had the consignee’s employee sign his paperwork stating he was hooked up to the proper connection. Consignee employee signed the paperwork and went inside the building. Driver proceeded to start the unloading process. OUR DRIVER MADE SEVERAL DIFFERENT MANUEVERS TO AVOID THE OUT OF CONTROL VEHICLE AND SEVERAL OTHER ACCIDENTS THAT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE WHITE VEHICLE.  THE TRUCK STRUCK THE WHITE VEHICLE IN THE REAR END SPINNING IT BACK AROUND.  WHEN THE WHITE VEHICLE THEN STRUCK THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK BEFORE COMING TO REST AGAINST THE MEDIAN.  OUR DRIVER TURNED BACK TOWARD THE COMING TO REST AGAINST THE MEDIAN.  OUR DRIVER TURNED BACK TOWARD THE MEDIAN HOPING TO BRING THE TRUCK TO REST WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED UP ON THE MEDIAN CAUSING IT AND THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN. column168: Operator was top loading material into the cargo tank.  Visually detected a leak at the fittings between hose connections.  Disconnected from source material, and attempted to pump lines dry.  Acted to disconnect hose fittings to replace gasket material.  Final loading hose section was not completely purged of liquid.  Upon disconnection, remaining liquid ran out of hose section and siphoned additional material from cargo tank.  Operator attempted to reconnect hose at fitting, slowing release.  Additional operator responded by removing hose section from top of cargo tank, relieving siphon.  Duration of release was approximately 30 seconds.  Operator took immediate defensive actions to contain released material and prevent migration from secondary containment area.  Notification of site Environmental and Safety officers was made within minutes.  Access to the area was controlled.  Emergency response contractor was called to the scene and arrived at 1100 hrs.  Effected clean up concluding at 1200 hrs.  Waste materials remain at site for proper classification and subsequent disposal.
column169: Procedures revised to require separation of fill hose section from liquid level in cargo tank prior to disconnection of any hose section.  Also added requirement of attendance by minimum of two operators when disconnecting hose sections from top loading operations.

THE SHIPPER CONTRACTED WITH AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE COMPANY TO INSPECT AND MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY FOUND THAT THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THUS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT UNDER THE MANWAY LID WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY TIGHTENED THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS AND INSPECTED THE OTHER FITTINGS ON THE CAR.  FINDING NO OTHER DEFECTS THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT WAS LIMITED TO THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  THE RESPONSE COMPANY WIPED DOWN THE TOP OF THE CAR TO REMOVE ANY LIQUID PRODUCT.

column168: COVERED HOPPER, IC765707, LOAD AMMONIUM NITRATE, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S SIBERT YARD IN MOBILE, AL.  PRODUCT WAS BEING RELEASED FROM A SPLIT WELD SEAM ON THE BOTTOM UNLOADING SHOOT JUST ABOVE THE SLIDE GATE ON THE "A" END COMPARTMENT.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO STOP THE LEAK AND CONDUCT THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP.  THE ALABAMA DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER, TERRA NITROGEN, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT THROUGH CHEMTREC.  THE SPLIT WAS INITIALLY PLUGGED WITH CLOTH RAGS TO STOP THE LEAK AND THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RECOVERED ABOUT 4,000 POUNDS OF PRODUCT FROM THE GROUND.  THE CONTRACTOR LATER MOUNTED A METAL PLATE OVER THE SPLIT IN THE SHOOT AND SECURED IT WITH BOLTS.  THE CONTRACTOR WILL TRANSFER PRODUCT FROM THE "B" END COMPARTMENT INTO THE "A" END COMPARTMENT TO BALANCE THE LOAD SO THAT THE CAR CAN BE MOVED TO DESTINATION.  THE CAR IS BEING HELD AT SIBERT YARD PENDING TERRA NITROGEN OBTAINING AN FRA APPROVAL TO ALLOW THE CAR TO CONTINUE TO MOVE.  TERRA NITROGEN IS TAKING THE SPILLED PRODUCT BACK TO ITS FACILITY FOR REPROCESSING.

THE CREW ON CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAIN, Q30206 REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, ACFX89895, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED PROPANOL WAS DIRPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CSXT'S TRAINMASTER FOR THAT TERRITORY RESPONDED AND REPORTED THAT THE BOTTOM OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS HANGING DOWN INDICATING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALAVE WAS OPEN.  HE RAISED AND SECURED THE OPERATING HANDLE WHICH CLOSED THE VALVE AND THE DROP STOPPED.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ON SCENE THEY INSPECTED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE EXTENSION PIPE AND THE BELL CAP.  BOTH WERE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CONTRACT ALSO WIRED THE LOCKING PIN FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE TO ENSURE THAT IT COULD NOT COME OUT IN TRANSPORTATION.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: PROX40710, LOAD METHANOL, WAS OBSERVED TO SPLASH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHILE IT WAS BEING SWITCHED AT CSX TRANPORTATIONS'S STANLEY YARD IN STANLEY, OHIO.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE SHIPPER, CELANESE CANADA WAS NOTIFIED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND NO INDICATION THAT THE CAR HAD RELEASED PRODUCT.  THE YARD TRAINMASTER HAD AN ENGINE COUPLE TO CAR AND SHAKE IT TO DETERMINE IF THERE WAS ANY LEAKAGE.  PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF THE "B" END PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE(PRD).  IT APPEARED THAT THE PRD WAS DEFECTIVE.  CELANESE WAS ADVISED OF THE DEFECT FOUND ON THE CAR AND RECOMMENEDED TO CONTACT A RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY TO RESPOND TO REPLACE THE PRD.  ON 02-14-05, RESCAR REPLACED THE "B" END PRD ON THE CAR.  RESCAR THEN PRESSURE TESTED THE CAR TO 35 PSIG.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  RESCAR REPORTED THAT IT APPEARED THAT THE PRD CAME APART INSIDE TANK.

column168: At approximately 1900 on Tuesday, February 2, 2005 the MMA Operations Control  Center in Herman, Maine received a call from the County Sheriffs Department advising that they had just received a call from a resident at Brownville Jct, Maine complaining of a strong sulphur smell and forming cloud near the railroad yard.    The Brownville Fire Department was notified immediately and given information relative to current Haz-Mat cars in the yard, location and emergency response information on the possible suspected problem molten sulfur cars.    MMA Manager Locomotive Operations, arrived about 1910, inspected two molten sulphur cars currently in the yard and discovered that TILX 135352 was emitting a strong sulphur smell (rotten Eggs). Inspection of the car found no evidence of leaking product and no cloud as previously reported. The weather was clear, with a very slight North West wind. The temperature was approximately 5 degrees.    The Brownville Fire Department arrived about 1910 and re-inspected the car and reviewed the hazards presented by the sulphur smell. The car moved to a remote location at the West end of Brownville Jct away from the residential area.  It was suspected that the rupture disc was bad and allowing some gases to escape.     On Febuary 4, 2005 the rupture disk was replaced by MMA Mechanical Forces, however the original one was inspected and found to be in good order.  Further inspection by MMA Mechanical and Transportation Supervisors noted that there was a hole rusted in the dome (not the tank) in the area of the dome lid hinge.      On February 8, 2005 the car was re-inspected by a Transportation Supervisor and no fumes were detected around or in the vicinity of the car.  Chemtrade was notified about the possible corrosive problem in the hinge area of the dome.  They advised that when the car was emptied it would be inspected and repaired.
column169: The shipper should have made closer inspection of the dome area and addressed any serious corrosion problems before the car was released for shipment to the rail carrier.

column162: MANAGER, DANGEROUS GOODS, SAFETY AND REGULATORY
column168: Wooden crate was shipped from Malpensa (MXP) Italy to Newark, NJ (EWR) then forwarded on to Tampa, FL (TPA).  Upon arrival of flight in TPA and subsequent unloading, it was discovered that liquid had leaked from the crate.      Inspection of the contents of the crate revealed two (2) bottles of Fuel, thought to be Kerosene, which had hoses attached to the lids.  These hoses were not clamped or closed to prevent release of contents.    Further inspection of contents revealed two (2) Non-Spillable batteries in close proximity to the fuel bottles.    It is estimated that between 5 and 10 milliters of fuel was released.      Continental Maintenance was contacted to clean-up spill and inspect aircraft cargo compartment for possible damage.  No damage to aircraft cargo compartment was observed.    The crate does not show evidence of damage.  Pictures of the crate and contents are available upon request.

column168: Eagle Driver Jim Haner was unloading gasoline at FasMart #21 on New Kent Highway when another motorist ran over our cones and struck delivery fitting knocking it loose causing approximately 30 gallons of gasoline to be released. The motorist fled the scene. No waterways were affetced. A ditch line was affected. Clean Harbors was contacted by Action Environmental on behalf of Eagle to respond to the spill. the spill area had been covered with absorbent material by a local fire department upon there arrival. Clean Harbor's recovered the absorbent material and a minor amount of soil that was affected by the release. No further action should be required.
column169: The spill was a result of negligence of an unknown motorist who fled the scene. The driver of the tanker was reportedly by the tanker and followed the appropriate procedures while off loading to the gasoline UST. Safety cones were reportedly in palce to barricade the off-loading area. No corrective actions should be required.

column168: Richard Heffernan delivered 36 gallons of propane into a 200 pound cylinder from a bulk truck. The cylinder was located at a residence in a trailer court. He drove away without disconnecting the hose on the bulk truck from the cylinder. Our investigation reveals that there was a release of  propane from the 200# cylinder because the filler valve on the Sherwood 2030C multivalve on the cylinder, failed to sheer away and initiate a backcheck valve closure, as required under UL 125.  Instead, the filler valve did not sheer but separated from the multivalve and destroyed the backcheck valve when the filler valve broke apart where it threaded to the multivalve. The propane caught fire and burned the trailer. The hose from the bulk truck leaked less than a gallon of propane. The ignition source is undetermined.
column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their piers covering the infraction they committed. Pull ways are regarded as very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: A ocean shipping container loaded with 20 drums of flammable liquids was in-transit from Venezuela to Canada through Elizabeth, NJ. When the container arrived in Elizabeth, there was a strong odor noticed. The container was impounded and the receiver was contacted. A third-pary inspector, cargo surveyor John F. Luard, was contacted to inspect the container. The container was found to have one leaking drum near the front of the container. A hazmat team from Clean Harbors was then contacted to remove, clean and repack the leaking drum and transfer the rest of the drums to a different ocean container. The original ocean container was then cleaned by the hazmat team.   The drum was leaking from the very bottom, along the seam. The hole was very small and it was very difficult to determine whether the liner in the drum failed or whether the drum was damaged during loading.
column169: The investigation has been started and will be completed once the product arrives at the final destination. The drum will then be thoroughly inspected to determine the root cause. Depending on the findings, appropriate remedial action will be implemented.

column168: At approximately 1025 hours, February 23, 2005, Jerul Thompson, Apria Healthcare Clinical Service Technician was replacing a fill hose on a truck mounted non-specification cargo tank, MVE HL190, serial #349. He proceeded to open the valve on the tank to pressurize the hose in order to check for leaks. The hose connection failed and an estimated one (1) pound of Oxygen, refrigerated liquid spilled. He received minor cryogenic burns on his lower right leg. He was transported to a local hospital where he was treated and released.    The Oxygen, refrigerated liquid fell onto a concrete pad where it vaporized.    There was no collateral damage or injuries as a rsult of this incident
column169: Examination of the hose connection revealed that connection had been cross-threaded. The hose has been replaced, with the damaged hose being removed to corporate for use as a training example.    As a result of this incident all members of the staff have received retraining on the operation of the vessel and the proper inspection procedures.

column168: RAILCAR NUMBER ACMX25676 WAS SWITCHED INTO THE AFTON FACILITY THE MORNING OF 2/4/05 BY KCS RAILROAD AND PLACED ON OUR UNLOADING SPOT "17-2".  STEAM WAS APPLIED TO THE CAR TO HEAT MATERIAL FOR UNLOADING.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS ON 2/4/05 THE CAR BEGAN TO LEAK MATERIAL FROM THE BELLY OF THE CAR.  THE STEAM WAS TURNED OFF AND THE MATERIAL WAS ALLOWED TO COOL.  THE MATERIAL LEAKED FOR A PERIOD OF 2.5 HOURS AND WAS ALL CONTAINED TO THE RAIL PAN LOCATED UNDERNEATH THE CAR.  APPROXIMATELY 9 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED.  THE SUPPLIER AND CAR OWNER, BP AMOCO, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM AND A REPAIR PLAN DEVELOPED.  THE CAR WAS SWITCHED OFF OF THE UNLOAD SPOT ON SATURDAY 2/5/04 AND PLACED ON OUR HOLD TRACK SPOT NUMBER "16-H".  THE FOLLOWING TUESDAY, 2/8/05, BP'S RAILCAR CONTRACTOR, RESCAR, AND AFTON CHEMICAL PERSONNEL REMOVED A PORTION OF THE OUTER INSULATING MATERIAL.  TWO CRACKS (22 INCHES AND 6 INCHES) WERE DISCOVERED ON THE BOTTOM SHELL OF THE RAILCAR.  THE CRACKS LOCATED HALF WAY BETWEEN THE OUTER JACKET SHIFT PLATE AND THE BRAKE PIVOT STUB ON THE "B" END OF THE CAR.  A REPAIR ATTEMPT WAS MADE BY APPLYING TITANIUM PUTTY TO FILL THE CRACKS.  A SECOND COAT OF PUTTY WAS APPLIED THE NEXT DAY, 2/9/05.  PICTURES OF THSI REPAIR ATTEMPT ARE ATTACHED.  THE CAR WAS SWITCHED BACK TO UNLOAD SPOT 17-2 ON 2/10/05 AND STEAM WAS AGAIN APPLIED TO THE CAR.  THE TITANIUM PUTTY APPLIED DID NOT HOLD AND THE CAR BEGAN TO LEAK AGAIN.  THE STEAM WAS AGAIN SHUTOFF AND THE LEAK EVENTUALLY STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS SWITCHED BACK TO THE HOLD TRACK 16-H ON 2/12/05 AND BP MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  2/14/05 UPDATE - BP AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM HULCHER SERVICES ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 0800.  HULCHER FABRICATED AND WELDED A BUCKET OVER THE CRACK.  THE CAR WAS THEN SWITCHED TO UNLOAD SPOT 17-2 AND HEATED.  2/15/05 - THE BUCKET REPAIR HELD AND ONLY A DE MINIMUS AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE REPAIR.  THE CAR WAS SUCESSFULLY UNLOADED ON 2/15/05.  THE CAR WILL BE SENT TO THE R/C SHOP FOR PERMANENT REPAIR.

column168: UPRR S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF LEAKING TANK CAR, GATX 24031 AT HERINGTON, KS.  SHANE KLEIN, MYO, ADVISED MR. SEKAVEC THAT APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT ONTO THE TIES.  HE ADVISED THAT ABSORBENT PADS HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE GROUND TO ASSIST ON CONTAINING THE PRODUCT.  MR. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO HERINGTON AND INSPECTED THE TANK.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP WAS FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT WHILE THE VALVE WAS CLOSED.  MR. SEKAVEC CYCLED THE VALVE THROUGH SEVERAL OPEN/CLOSE MOVEMENTS TO TRY TO GET THE VALVE TO RESEAT AND STOP LEAKING WITHOUT SUCCESS.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED TO SECURE THE VALVE AND STOP THE LEAK.  MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED PAT LOFTUS WITH QUADRA ENERGY (SHIPPER) TO ADVISE HIM OF THE PROBLEM.  MR. SEKAVEC SUGGESTED THAT THE FRA BE CONSULTED TO DETERMINE IF THE CAR COULD BE MOVED TO DESTINATION UNDER A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL TO BE UNLOADED AND THEN ROUTED FOR REPAIR.  MR. SEKAVEC MADE A REQUEST OF THE FRA FOR A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL ON BEHALF OF QUADRA ENERGY, WHICH WAS GRANTED.  THE CAR WAS RECHECKED TO VERIFY THE CAP WAS SECURED AND THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.  TWO FIVE-GALLON BUCKETS OF GASOLINE-CONTAMINATED WASTE (BALLAST AND ABSORBENT PADS) WERE GENERATED FROM THIS INCIDENT.  QUADRA ENERGY WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE.
column169: INSURE VALVE IS SECURED PRIOR TO RELEASE OF THE TANK CAR.

column168: SERVICE TRANSPORT DRIVER MICHAEL SCALLY WAS DRIVING SOUTH ON LA HIGHWAY #90 NEAR BROUSSARD, LA.  HE WAS TRANSPORTING A TANKER LOAD OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S., 3 UN 1993 LOADED AT CHAMPIONS TECHNOLOGY FRESNO, TX CONSIGNED TO CHAMPIONS TECHNOLOGY, BROUSSARD, LA.  THE DRIVER MISSED THE TURNOFF (IDA ROAD) AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO CROSS OVER BACK TO THE NORTHBOUND SIDE WHEN HIS TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY A TRACTOR DRIVEN BY ERIC BAGWELL.  THE COLLISION SPUN THE TRAILER AROUND AND CAUSE THE UNIT TO ROLLOVER IN THE MEDIAN.  OUR DRIVER HAD SLOWED DOWN AND WAS ATTEMPTING TO TURN FROM THE OUTSIDE LANE TO INSIDE LANE TO EFFECT THE CROSSOVER.  WHEN MR. BAGWELL STRUCK THE REAR OF OUR TRAILER AT A SPEED OF APPROXIMATELY 65 MPH, BAGWELL WAS PULLED A REEFER UNIT FULL OF OYSTERS.  THIS LOUISIANA STATE POLICE RESPONDED ALONG WITH THE BROUSSARD LA POLICE - AN EMS UNIT WAS CALLED.  BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN TO LAFAYETTE GENERAL HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION - NEITHER WERE INJURED.  THE LA HAZMAT HOTLINE WAS CALLED - INCIDENT REPORT #051105 GIVEN - HAT. RESPONSE CALLED.  NO SPILL OCCURRED - SERVICE TRANSPORT SAFETY MANAGERS AND EAGLE EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNDER DIRECTION OF LA HAZMAT TROPPER PESTON SUMMERS.
column169: DRIVER MICHAEL SCALLY WAS INTERVIEWED EXTENSIVELY ABOUT THE ACCIDENT.  AFTER COLLECTING ALL THE FACTS AND SCRUTINIZING CAREFULLY, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ACCIDENT'S ROOT CAUSE WAS RIVER ERROR.  THE DRIVER PERFORMED AN UNSAFE TURN - DUE TO THIS ACTION AND THE CONCLUSION THAT THE DRIVER CANNOT BE TRUSTED TO DRIVE SAFELY, MR. SCALLY WAS TERMINATED.  OUR DRIVER TRAINING PROGRAM COVERS THESE TYPES OF SAFE OPERATING PROCEDURES AND SHALL BE REINFORCED.  ALL DRIVER SAFETY MEETING FOR THE REMAINDER OF YEAR 2005 WILL REFRESH THESE SAFETY REQUIREMENTS - (SAFE DRIVING AWARENESS)

column168: VERN LIBBY, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, REPORTED CONTAINER PONU 785727 HAD BEEN INSPECTED BY THE FRA AND A 943 LITER TOTE WAS FOUND LEAKING, HOWEVER, NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.  HE INSTRUCTED RMCC TO MAKE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC FOR SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE CONTACT.  STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  SEAL 0000870 MID PLTF WAS REMOVED AND THE DOORS OPENED FOR INTERIOR INSPECTION, WITH NO BLOCKING AND BRACING NOTICED.  INTERIOR INSPECTION DEVELOPED THAT THE TOTE, WHICH WAS LOCATED IN THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER NEAR THE DOOR, HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM THE TOP CLOSURE CAP.  THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE CONTAINED TO THE EXTERIOR OF THE TOTE AND THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER.  TIM TOPOLINSKI, DOW CORNING, MIDLAND, MI. CONTRACTED DIRECTLY WITH JASON BLAIR, NRC, SEATTLE, WA. TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP.  THE LEAKING TOTE WAS REMOVED AND STORED IN CONTAINER, POCU 065117 PENDING DISPOSITION.  CONTAINER PONU 785727 WAS CLEANED AND REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED AND THE DOORS CLOSED.  IT WAS SEALED WITH SEAL UPS-116305 AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  A NEW CLOSURE CAP WAS MAILED TO SEATTLE AND PLACED ON THE TOTE IN QUESTION.  ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE WAS REMOVED AND TAKEN TO NRC'S FACILITY RENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.  BLAIR ESTIMATED THE COST OF CLEANUP AT APPROXIMATELY $7500.00  RANDY BOYINGTON, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR, FROM THE FRA, SEATTLE, WA. ALSO NOTED THE CONTAINER HAD IMPROPER PLACARDS.  THE CORROSIVE AND FLAMMABLE PLACARDS ON THE DOORS WERE TORN WITH PORTIONS OF THE PLACARDS MISSING.  FURTHER ON THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION THERE WAS BOTH A CORROSIVE AND A FLAMMABLE PLACARD.  HOWEVER, THE FLAMMABLE PLACARD CLASS NUMBER WAS MARKED IN WHITE WITH THE ROMAN NUMERAL III INSTEAD OF THE NUMBER 3 AS REQUIRED.  INSPECTION FURTHER NOTED WAYBILL 291402 DATED 02/02/2005 TO LIST CORROSIVE LIQUID ACIDIC ORGANIC N.O.S. (ACETOXYSILANE) ONLY.  FURTHER INTERIOR INSPECTION LOCATED THE PACKING LIST WHICH IDENTIFIES FOUR 55 GALLON DRUMS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S. (XYLENE/ETHYLBENZENE) TO ALSO BE LOADED IN THE CONTAINER.  THE WAYBILL WAS CORRECTED TO REFLECT THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID.

column168: ANN, UNION PACIFIC, REPORTED CONTAINER TPHU 483461 LEAKED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE AT THE LATC YARD IN LOS ANGELES, CA.  ANN STATED THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 828.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR. COOPER STATED TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ALSO ENROUTE.  AT 01:09 PM, COOPER REPORTED THE CONTAINER WAS STILL ON THE RAIL CAR, BUT NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING AT THIS TIME.  DRIED RESIDUE WAS NOTED ON THE RAILCAR, BELOW THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER.  MR. COOPER ADVISED THE PH LEVEL OF THE SUBSTANCE WAS LOW, AND THE SUBSTANCE APPEARS TO BE A NON-REGULATED COMMODITY THAT HAD LEAKED FROM THE CONTAINER WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE RAILCAR AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED FOR INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, NOTED A SINGLE BAND OF TY GARD USED TO RESTRAIN THE LADING.  THIS IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE6C, FOR THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES, NOR IS IT AN ADEQUATE SECUREMENT OF THE TOTAL VOLUME OF LADING.  SEVERAL 30 GALLON POLY DRUMS OF NON REGULATED MATERIALS WERE NOTED TOPPLED NEAR THE TOP TIER MID SECTION OF THE LADING.  THE ENTIRE LOAD HAD COMMODITIES IMPROPERLY STRETCH WRAPPED, NOT SECURED TO PALLETS, AND LACKING ADEQUATE WRAP TO RESTRAIN THE WEIGHT OF THE LADING.  FOUR METAL DRUMS, LOADED ON A PALLET AT THE LEFT REAR FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER, HAD ABRADED AGAINST THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER.  ONE DRUM WAS EMPTY, ONE LOST APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS, AND THE REMAINING TWO DRUMS THAT DID NOT LEAK, WERE SO SEVERELY DAMAGED FROM BRADING THE ADJACENT DRUMS, THEY WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORT.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUMS.  A SINGLE PIECE OF STRETCH WRAP HAD BENE APPLIED AROUND THE TOP HEAD OF THE DRUMS, WHICH IS INADEQUATE TO KEEP THE DRUMS FROM MOVING.  THE PRODUCT, ZEP BRAKE WASH, WAS LABELED AS A FLAMMABLE.  THE NEXT ROW IN, AN UNDERSIZED PALLET CONTAINED FOUR METAL DRUMS OF ZEP X4402, ALSO LABELED AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  ONE DRUM LOST APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM A THREE INCH CRACK UNDER THE TOP CHINE, CAUSED FROM ABRADING AGAINST AN ADJACENT DRUM.  THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE DAMAGED SUFFICIENTLY ENOUGH FROM ABRADING THE ADJACENT DRUMS, THAT THEY WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  THIS SET OF DRUMS ALSO HAVE A SINGLE APPLICATION OF STRETCH WRAP AROUND THE TOP HEADS OF THE DRUMS.  FURTHER INTO THE LADING, LOCATED A SINGLE BOX LABELED CORROSIVE, THAT WAS SITTING ON TOP OF PALLETIZED CARTONS OF ANOTHER COMMODITY, TOTALLY UNSECURED.  A SHORT DISTANCE TO THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, LOCATED A FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL LABELED POISON, THAT WAS ALSO SITTING ON TOP OF PALLETIZED CARTONS, TOTALLY UNSECURED.  NEAR THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, LOCATED A PALLET OF ZEP RING MASTER ANGLE NECK, A NON REGULATED TOILET BOWL CLEANER.
column169: SEVERAL CARTONS HAD BROKEN FREE FROM THE STRETCH WRAP AND TOPPLED INTO THE FRONT AND SIDE VOIDS AROUND THE PALLET AN ADJACENT LADING.  THE CARTONS HAD BECOME SATURATED FROM PRODUCT LEAKING FROM LOOSE CAP CLOSURES OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES.  NUMEROUS CARTONS HAD TO BE BAGGED TO PREVENT ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  THE LIQUID TOILET BOWL CLEANER WAS CONSISTANT WITH THE PRODUCT OBSERVED ON THE RAILCAR.  THE RAILCAR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND RELEASED BACK INTO SERVICE FOR RELOADING.  A TOTAL OF EIGHT DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND RESTOWED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER ALONG WITH THE OTHER LADING.  THE LADING WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASE FOR OVER THE ROAD MOVEMENT TO CORONA.  REVIEW PROPER LOADING AND RESTRAINT PROTOCOLS.

column168: AT 10:08 AM ON 02-28-05 FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY SENIOR MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, STEVE CARMICHAEL, AND ADVISED THAT CONDUCTOR STEVE PRIDGEN HAD REPORTED COMING IN CONTACT WITH A WHITE CRYSTALINE POWDER OFF OF TANK CAR TLDX 216028 WHILE BEING SWITCHED IN THE STRANG YARD, LA PORTE, TX.  UPON COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE POWDER, MR. PRIDGEN WASHED DOWN AT A NEARBY SAFETY SHOWER, AND WENT HOME TO CHANGE CLOTHES.  AFTER BEING NOTIFIED, MGR LERCH RESPONDED.  ON ARRIVAL, HE NOTED THE SIDES OF CAR TO BE COVERED WITH DRIED PRODUCT, AND OBSERVED THE TOP AROUND THE MAN WAY NOZZLE MOIST WITH LIQUID PRODUCT.  ADDITIONALLY, THE ADJACENT CAR UTLX 910146 WAS NOTED WITH DRIED PRODUCT ON THE "B" END OF THE CAR.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE CAR TLDX 216028 REVEALED THE MANWAY GASKET TO BE MISPOSITIONED ON THE NOZZLE, AND THREE OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS IN POSITION, BUT NOT WRENCH TIGHT.  AFTER DETERMINING SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MGR LERCH ADVISED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER CONTACT VIA CHEM-TREC.  ON ARRIVAL OF SHIPPER PERSONNEL BOTH CARS WERE CLEANED AND NEUTRALIZED.  A NEW GASKET WAS CORRECTLY POSITIONED ON THE NOZZLE OF TLDX 216028 AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS CLOSED AND PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 7TH, 2005, TANK CARS ADMX 29274 CONTAINING ALCOHOL AND ADMX 15486 CONTAINING CORN SWEETENER, DERAILED AT THE WEST END OF THE MARSHALLTOWN YARD.  BOTH CARS WERE DERAILED ON THEIR SIDES, AND NO LEAKS WERE INITIALLY DETECTED.  DURING THE RE-RAILING OPERATION, TANK CAR ADMX 29274 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A CRACK AT THE BOTTOM OF A DENT.  THE INITIAL TANK RATE WAS ESTIMATED AT APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON EVERY THREE MINUTES.  THE LEAK WAS INITIALLY SLOWED DOWN TO A DRIP WHILE THE CAR WAS RE-RAILED.  AFTER RE-RAILING, THE CRACK WAS SECURED WITH A PATCH, AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  ON FEBRUARY 8TH, 2005, THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERED TO TANK CAR ADMX 29382, AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  BASED ON INSPECTIONS PERFORMED PRIOR TO RE-RAILING BY REPRESENTATIVES OF HYDROKLEAN SERVICES, AND MARK MADAY, MGR-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, THE TANK CAR ADMX 29274 WAS NOT LEAKING WHILE IT WAS ON ITS SIDE.  THE CAR STARTED LEAKING AFTER RE-RAILING OPERATIONS STARTED.

column168: ARTURO TALAMANTEZ, CAR FOREMAN, ADVISED YARD PERSONNEL DETECTED AN UNPLEASANT ODOR NEAR TANKCAR GATX 11125 WHICH WAS LOCATED ON A RIP TRACK AT THE RAIL YARD IN EAGLE PASS, TX.  PAUL PERSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED.  STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATORY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 09:19 AM, PERSON ADVISED THAT AFTER INVESTIGATION RESIDUE TANKCAR GATX 11125 VENTED DUE TO A PRESSURE DIFFERENTIAL, CAUSED BY A CHANGE IN TEMPERATURE FROM A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET PLATE.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR HAD BEEN TRANSFERED IN ST. LOUIS, MO. EARLIER IN THE MONTH.  THE CAR CONTAINED LESS THAN 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT CAUSING THE VAPOR RELEASE.  MR. PERSON ADVISED HE WOULD MEET WITH PERSONNEL FROM DOW CHEMICAL AND REMEDIATE THE PROBLEM.  DOW CHEMICAL AND EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED WITH PAUL PERSON TO ADDRESS THE SITUATION.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO SPOFFORD, TEX TO BE STEAM CLEANED AND PURGED.

AT 12:48 PM ON 02/15/05, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT REGINALD STUBBLEFIELD, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANK CAR DUPX 29205, LOCATED IN BOWL TRACK 2, STRANG YARD, LAPORTE, TX. LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  MR. STUBBLEFIELD FURTHER ADVISED THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.  MGR LERCH RESPONDED AND ADVISED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY TWO DROPS A SECOND WITH NO POOLING OF PRODUCT.  MGR LERCH IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE DRAIN HOLE ON THE SKID PROTECTION TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS DUE TO SHELL FAILURE BEHIND THE SKID PROTECTION.  UPON DETERMINING SOURCE OF THE LEAK, MGR LERCH SECURED A TEMPORARY PLUG INTO THE SKID PROTECTION DRAIN HOLE.  ON ARRIVAL OF SHIPPER PERSONNEL, ADDITIONAL SEALING MATERIAL WAS SECURED AROUND THE TEMPORARY PLUG INTO THE SKID PROTECTION DRAIN HOLE.  ON ARRIVAL OF SHIPPER PERSONNEL, ADDITIONAL SEALING MATERIAL WAS SECURED AROUND THE TEMPORARY PLUG TO FURTHER SECURE THE CAR FROM RELEASE.  THE SHIPPER THEN MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED BACK TO THEIR FACILITY ACROSS THE STREET TO OFF LOAD AND SHOP THE CAR FOR NECESSARY REPAIRS.  NO ADDITIONAL REMEDIATION WAS REQUIRED DUE TO THE MATERIAL EVAPORATING UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.  AT 05:00 PM, TANK CAR DUPX 29205 WAS SWITCHED TO DUPONT FOR OFF LOADING AND FURTHER HANDLING.

WHILE PERFORMING RANDOM TANK CAR INSPECTIONS IN TOPEKA, KS, MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DISCOVERED GATX 81138 (RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED ALCOHOLS, N.O.S.) RELEASING VAPOR FROM THE MANWAY COVER.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED AND A DEFECTIVE GASKET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A GASKET FASHIONED FROM GORE-TEX.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS CLOSED AND RESECURED SO THAT THE CAR COULD CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.
column169: SHIPPER NEEDS TO INSURE THAT THE MANWAY GASKET IS IN GOOD CONDITION PRIOR TO RELEASING THE TANK CAR.

column58: Cover; O-Ring or Seals; Vacuum Relief Valve
column168: WHILE PERFORMING RANDOM TANK INSPECTIONS IN TOPEKA, KS, MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY AND LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DISCOVERED UTLX 203395 (LOADED, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.) RELEASING VAPOR FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS POPPED SEVERAL TIMES IN AN EFFORT TO RESEAT THE VALVE WITHOUT SUCCESS.  THE SHIPPER (WESTERN PLAINS ENERGY) WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM.  MR. SEKAVEC SUGGESTED THAT THE VALVE BE REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A PLUG SO THAT THE CAR COULD CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL WOULD BE REQUIRED FROM THE FRA AND MR. SEKAVEC ADVISED WESTERN PLAINS THAT HE WOULD ASSIST THEM IN OBTAINING THE APPROVAL.  MR. SEKAVEC CONTACT WITH LOUIS RODRIGUEZ, MECHANICAL FOREMAN, TO ADVISE HIM OF THE VALVE PROBLEM AND REQUESTED THAT MR. RODRIGUEZ PLACE THE CAR IN BAD-ORDER STATUS TO PREVENT THE CAR FROM DEPARTING PRIOR TO THE REPAIR BEING MADE.  ON FRIDAY 2/18/05, MR. SEKAVEC CHECKED THE UPRR COMPUTER TO DETERMINE WHERE THE CAR WAS LOCATED SO THAT THE PLUG COULD BE INSTALLED PRIOR TO THE CAR MOVING AND FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS ENTRAINED ON THE MTPNPX-15 AND HAD ALREADY PASSED PAWNEE, NE.  ME. SEKAVEC CONTACTED KIM KEELING, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, AND REQUESTED THAT MR. KEELING MEET THE CAR IN NORTH PLATTE, NE, AND REMOVE THE DEFECTIVE VALVE AND REPLACE IT WITH A PLUG.  MR. KEELING WAS ABLE TO COMPLETE THE REPAIR ON 2/20/05 AND THE FRA ISSUED A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL (FRA-05020061) ON 2/24/05.  THE CAR THEN CONTINUED IN TRANSPORTATION TO STOCKTON, CA, WHERE THE TANK WAS TO BE UNLOADED AND THEN REQUALIFIED PRIOR TO BEING RELOADED.
column169: REMOVE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICES FROM TANK CAR SERVICE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0950 DOCKWORKER KEVIN TAYLOR WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER WHICH AND HAD NOTICED A LIQUID SUBSTANCE LEAKING.  BENNETT RO BETWEEN, A WELL CLOSED DEVICES IN HAZ-MAT.  HAZ MAT KNOWELDGE THAT TOLD LEVIN MY SELF OF HOW DANGEROUS CHEMICAL THIS IS.  BONNOFF AND I PUSHED THE RELEASED AMOUNT OF ACID BY THIS TIME ABOUT 32-4002 HAD SPILLED IN A 30 MINUTES TIME FRAME.
