column168: AT AVON YARD, THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT WAS INSPECTING THE CARS FOR OUTBOUND TRAIN Q364.  THE CARMAN FOUND A DRIP LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF TANK CAR DBUX 300035.  CSX HAZMAT DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED AT 22:37.  HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL CALLED TO PERFORM CLEANUP OF LEAK.  22:52 CHEMTREC NOTIFIED, GIVEN REPORT #02252005104.  01:17 HERITAGE HAD TIGHTENED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, VERIFIED VALVE WAS CLOSED, STOPPED LEAK.

column168: I went to a smoke and coffee break after my 1st load that Was around 8:OOpm to  8:30pm..... . . . . . . . . . .When I completed loading the product I went inside dispatch to drop off the manifest to Maria Kemp Orlando, Jermaine, Ray and Edwin were there mingling Maria Kemp asked one of the three drivers to accompany me for the Cocos Island delivery None of the drivers wanted to go Orlando was not sure It he wanted to go Jenrnaine also was unsure that he wanted to go Ray didn’t say anything I didn’t want to force the other drivers tø go, because they were done with their loackand I know they wanted to go home I got my documents and proceeded to the truck and heard Maria Kemp ask “Orlando do you want to gö?" I inspected the truck prior to leaving and Orlando approached the truck as I was leaving the terminal On the way clown to the delivery site, Orlando asked me at the bridge to drop him off at Inn on the Bay I told Orlando that I cant make a stop, but he mnssted Although I did not make a complete stop, I slowed down enough, so Orlando can get off the truck I had radio contact with him and I told him to make sure that lie Is there when I get back from my delivery, because I can’t make a stop.  I proceeded to the job site.  After the look out, Cotti bay 802, I shifted down from 5th to 4th gear.  On the way down I could smell a burning smell that appeared to be either the smell of burning Brakes or Clutch.  After I passed the Morrison's house, Approaching the steep hill after the umatac look-out, I made the engine brake do most of the work applying the brakes periodically along the way.  The engine brakes were on.  I was traveling 20 miles an hour, but no more than 25 miles an hour.  When I applied the brakes again I was touching the deck.  I couldn't stop the truck anywhere, because of the homes and there was no space and all other options were too dangerous to pull over and stop.  i shifted down from 4th to 3rd gear.  I felt the weight of the load pushing the truck down.  When I was 3rd gear, I heard a snap.  it sounded like the brake springs were snapping.  Pretty much at the corner at the bottom of the hill, I heard the same snapping sound, then the brakes failed.  My air pressure was still at 75-80, then the engine brake shut down and then I applied the brakes but could not slow down the truck.  Pijfroac hod the corner, trying to control tilE truck b swerving on Ito the oncoming lane to be abbi to make the approaching turn and hoping to have a direct approach into the village of timatac The truck rolled over on its passenger sIde and skidded on its side into the power pole, I landed on the passenger side, I blacked out for a few seconds and when I regained consciousness and I suddenly saw and felt heat and a gush of diesel fuel bit m in the face and body I pushed backwards and rolled out of the truck through the buste ci windshield When I got out of the truck, the truck was still running but was surrounded by flames  I ran down the hill looking

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT PHELPS DODGE MORENCI FACILITY, THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO UNLOAD AT THE REDUCTION WORKS ACID TANK.  AFTER DONNING FULL PPE, THE DRIVER STARTED THE UNLOADING.  WHEN THE DRIVER CONNECTED TO THE INLET FOR UNLOADING, THE TANK LEVEL LIGHT WAS AMBER IN COLOR, WHICH INDICATES ENOUGH ROOM IN THE TANK TO BEGIN UNLOADING.  THE DRIVER BEGIN UNLOADING AND WALKED TO THE FRONT OF HIS TRUCK TO PERFORM AN INSPECTION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FRONT, HE NOTICED THAT THE TANK LEVEL LIGHT HAD TURNED RED.  HE IMMEDIATELY RETURNED TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK AND CLOSED THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES.  THIS STOPS THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE TRAILER STILL SHOWED LOADED NEAR TO FULL.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE SECURITY GATE TO INFORM THE PERSONNEL AT THE GATE OF THE SITUATION.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO CHANGE UNLOADING LOCATIONS TO THE STARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO DISCONNECT THE HOSE FROM THE TANK INLET CONNECTION.  UPON BREAKING THE CONNECTION, ACID SPRAYED ONTO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE DRIVER WASHED DOWN THE AREA OF THE TRAILER WHICH WAS IMPACTED BY THE ACID SPRAY AND WASHED HIS PPE IN THE WASH AREA.  THE DRIVER THEN CLOSED UP THE TRAILER AND MOVED TO THE STARGO TANK AS INSTRUCTED.  AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER CALLED THE CARRIER DISPATCHER, BOB WEST, TO REPORT THE ACID SPRAY RELEASE.  THE DISPATCHER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO IMMEDIATELY CONTACT THE SECURITY GUARDS AND REPORT THE INCIDENT.  AFTER UNLOADING AT THE STARGO TANK, PDMI SECURITY TRANSPORTED THE DRIVER TO THE LOCAL CLINIC FOR POSSIBLE EXPOSURE.  THE CLINIC REPORTED NO INJURIES WERE RECEIVED AND NO EXPOSURE AS WELL.
column169: THE CARRIER SAFETY DIRECTOR REVIEWED THEIR WRITTEN POLICIES WITH THE TERMINAL MANAGER.  ALL PROCEDURES HAVE BEEN REVIEWED WITH THE DRIVER INVOLVED.  TERMINAL MANAGER REVIEWED THE CAUSE WITH ALL PDMI DRIVER PERSONNEL TO ASSURE COMPLIANCE.

column168: ON 02/17/05 AT 1030HRS J. PIZZA MGR. OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE CONTACTED CTS MGR. M. KELLY ADVISED THAT ONE OF HIS CARMEN WHILE INSPECTING AN INBOUND TRAIN HAD DISCOVERED THE ABOVE TANK CAR LEAKING OUT THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE AREA WHERE THE HEX HEAD BOLTS ATTACHED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO THE SHELL OF THE TANK.  KELLY TIGHTENED THE BOLTS BUT WAS STILL UNABLE TO STOP THE LEAK.  KELLY THEN CONTACTED DENIIS WOOSTED WITH DOW CHEMICAL ABOUT THE CAR.  MR. WOOSTER ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS AND THE THAT CONTRACTOR THAT DID THE REPAIR WORK HAD PLACED THE WRONG BOTTOM OUTLET GASKET IN THE CAR.  WOOSTER ADVISED THAT HE WOULD SHIP THE PROPER GASKET OVERNIGHT TO KELLY.  KELLY PURGED AND CLEANED THE CAR WITH STEAM AND REPLACED THE OLD GASKET WITH THE NEW ONE SHIPPED FROM DOW.  ON 02/21/05 THE CAR WAS LEAKED TESTED TO 30PSI BY UNION TANK CAR CO. COPIES OF THE TEST WERE FORWARD TO DOW.

column168: DAVID, HINKLE TRAINMASTER, ADVISED RMCC THAT TANKCAR GATX 73735, WAS LEAKING HYDROGEN PEROXIDE ON HUMP TRUCK 138, OF THE HINKLE YARD IN HERMISTON, OR.  SANDY, HERMISTION EMERGENCY DISPATCHER, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED THAT EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WOULD BE DISPATCHED.  THE HERMISTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO SCENE AND CONFIRMED THAT TANKCAR GATX 73735, WAS NOT LEAKING AT TIME OF THEIR INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO FIRES OBSERVED BY FIRE DEPARTMENT.  YARD WAS EVACUATED FOR SHORT DURATION AT DIRECTION OF OPERATING PERSONNEL; UNTIL ERNIE SIROTEK ADVISED SILER AND KEN HUNT THAT CAR WAS NOT IN DANGER OF EXPLODING.  TANKCAR GATX 73735 WAS ISOLATED TO LOAD SHIFTER TRACK.  RMCAT EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR INSPECTED CAR AND ADVISED NO ACTIVE LEAK OBSERVED.  NO LEAK EVIDENT FROM VENT FITTINGS.  SMALL TRACE OF FLUID AT POROUS STONE FITTING.  ALL BOLTS TIGHT.  RICK SLOANE INSPECTED CAR APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM PST ON 2/28/05.  REPORTED NO SOURCE OF LEAK EXCEPT MINUTE AMOUNT OF FLUID UNDER POROUS STONE FITTINGS SIMILAR TO RMCAT FINDINGS.  CAR RELEASED BY SLOANE FOR MOVEMENT.
column169: INCIDENT WAS ANOMALOUS.  REOCCURRENCE UNLIKELY.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: UPRR S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANK CAR TO BE LEAKING TO TOPEKA, KS.  MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED LOUIS RODRIGUEZ, MECHANICAL FOREMAN,WHO REPORTED NATX 300011 (RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES) WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  MR. RODRIGUEZ PLACED A BUCKET BELOW THE VALVE TO MINIMIZE THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST TO THE GROUND.MR. SEKAVEC PROCEEDED TO TOPEKA, INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND DETERMINED THE PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  MR. SEKAVEC REMOVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP AND CYCLED THE CAP OPEN AND CLOSED SEVERAL TIMES IN AN ATTEMPT TO RESEAT THE VALVE WITHOUT SUCCESS.  MR. SEKAVEC ALSO MADE CONTACT WITH RUN TULEY, MGP INGREDIENTS AND DETERMINED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN LOADED AT MGP IN ATCHISON, KS, AND WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE PLANT.  THE CAR WAS UNLOADED AND ROUTED TO MILLENNIUM RAIL IN JUNCTION CITY, KS, FOR REPAIR.  MR. SEKAVEC WAS ABLE TO POSITION THE VALVE BALL SO THAT A VERY MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS BEING RELEASED  AND THEN REMOVED THE VALVE HANDLE SO THAT THE VALVE COULD NOT BE INADVERTENTLY OPENED.  HE THEN SECURED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP TO PREVENT ANY PRODUCT FROM ESCAPING.  MR. SEKAVEC ADVISED MR. TULEY OF THE PROBLEM AND THE TEMPORARY REPAIR AND ADVISED THAT THE FRA WOULD NEED TO ISSUE A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL FOR THE CAR  TO CONTINUE ON TO DESTINATION.  (FRA-05020065 ISSUED TO PROTECT MOVEMENT OF THIS CAR TO DESTINATION.)  APPROXIMATELY ONE TO TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD COLLECTED BELOW THE CAR BUT EVAPORATED QUICKLY WITH NO NEED FOR REMEDIATION.THE PRODUCT THAT HAD COLLECTED IN THE BUCKET WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE CAR FOR DISPOSAL BY THE REPAIR FACILITY.
column169: VALVE SHOULD HAVE BEEN REPAIRED OR SECURED PRIOR TO MOVEMENT OF THE CAR OUT OF THE PLANT.

column168: LEON HENDRICKSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TANKCAR GAMX 6124, ON TRAIN QHKNP 27, AT THE YARD IN POCATELLO, ID.  MR. HENDRICKSON ADVISED SIL MARTINEZ, SENIOR AGENT - HAZMAT WAS ON SCENE AND A SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL WAS ON THE GROUND.  TOM FLORES, CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 09:45 AM, HENDRICKSON ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED ON DEPOT TRACK NUMBER FOUR AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  A NEW GASKET WAS PLACED ON THE THEMOMETER WELL.  PACIFIC WEST HANDLED THE CLEANUP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE TANK CAR.

column168: A LEAKING RESIDUE ETHANOL CAR, THE NATX 38390, WAS REPORTED BY A CAR FOREMAN.  THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM FROM THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR AND THE TOTAL VOLUME RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED AT ONE PINT.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPROTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED, AND HAD REPRENSENTATIVES FROM HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, INC., A HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, INSPECT THE CAR.  MARK REIMERS LATER REPORTED THAT THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PARTIALLY OPEN LIQUID VALVE.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND SECURED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  NO CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY AS NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.
column169: THE UNLOADER OF THE CAR WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED TO COMMUNICATE THE ISSUES WITH THE EMPLOYEES THAT HAD UNLOADED THE CAR AND FAILED TO CLOSE AND SECURE THE VALVE.

column168: A CAR FOREMAN REPORTED TANKCAR NATX 301129 WAS LEAKING ETHANOL FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK ORIGINATED FROM UNDERNEATH THE MOUNTING FLANGE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE LEAK RATE WAS ONE DROP EVERY FOUR TO FIVE SECONDS.  MR. REIMERS ADVISED THE TANKCAR COULD NOT BE REPAIRED AND THE SHIPPER PROVIDED TRUCKS TO TRANSFER THE TANKCAR.  AFTER THE TRANSFER, THE CAR WAS SENT TO A SHOP FOR REPAIRS.
column169: PROPER INSPECTION PROCEDURES WILL BE REINFORCED WITH THE UNION PACIFIC SWITCH CREW.
